{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7b05afc1-9e85-48cf-911d-29c692a0b23a","content":"The tutorial you found is **outdated**. Here's the correct guidance for .NET MAUI on .NET 10:\n\n### `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` — ❌ Not needed\n\nThis was a **Xamarin.Forms** platform-specific. In .NET MAUI, safe area padding is applied **automatically** on iOS by default — you don't need to opt in. Content pages already respect the safe area insets without any extra attribute.\n\n### `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` — ✅ Still valid\n\nIf you want a layout (like a `Grid` with a background image) to extend **behind** the notch/status bar, you can use:\n\n```xml\n<Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\nThis tells that specific layout to ignore the safe area and extend edge-to-edge.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Property | Status in .NET 10 MAUI |\n|----------|----------------------|\n| `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` | Removed — safe area is automatic |\n| `IgnoreSafeArea` | Valid on layouts to go edge-to-edge |\n\nSo just drop the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` line entirely, and use `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` only on layouts you explicitly want to bleed into unsafe areas.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"07a0d7de-c577-466f-b2c0-c1e2fc61fa29","outputTokens":339,"requestId":"0808:260325:434E2:4F15C:69F2AB5C"},"id":"515b1b03-9a5d-4e76-9229-d402f3971592","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:07:48.113Z","parentId":"3519d2fd-c0bf-45a8-a743-223684e07da1"}
